{"title_page": "Carron Company", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=July 2009}}\n[[File:Carron Company trademark.jpg|thumb|right|The Carron Company [[trademark]] on the Carron Works]]\n[[File:Carron Company insignia.JPG|thumb|Carron Company insignia]]\nThe '''Carron Company''' was an [[ironworks]] established in 1759 on the banks of the [[River Carron (Forth)|River Carron]] near [[Falkirk]], in [[Stirlingshire]], Scotland.  After initial problems, the company was at the forefront of the [[Industrial Revolution]] in the [[United Kingdom]].  The company prospered through its development and production of a new short-range and short-barrelled naval [[cannon]], the [[carronade]].  The company was one of the largest iron works in Europe through the 19th century.  After 223 years, the company became [[insolvency|insolvent]] in 1982 and was later acquired by the [[Franke (company)|Franke Corporation]], being rebranded '''Carron Phoenix'''.\n\n==Early years==\n[[File:Clocktower entrance to the former Carron Works, near Falkirk.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Clocktower entrance to the Carron Works]]\n[[File:Dated iron lintel at the former Carron Works, near Falkirk.jpg|thumb|right|Fragment of the first [[blast furnace]] in the clocktower of the Carron Works]]\n[[File:James Watt steam engine relic at the Carron Works.JPG|thumb|right|[[Cylinder (engine)|Cylinder]] fragment of [[James Watt|Watt]]'s first operational [[steam engine]] at the Carron Works]]\n\nThe original founders of the Carron Works were: [[John Roebuck]], a [[medical doctor]] and [[chemist]] from [[Sheffield]]; his two brothers, Thomas Roebuck and Ebenezer Roebuck; [[Samuel Garbett]], a merchant from [[Birmingham]]; [[William Cadell]], Senior, an [[industrialist]] from a merchant family, from [[Cockenzie]], [[East Lothian]]; his son, William Cadell, Junior; and John Cadell.<ref name=\"GfS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.scottish-places.info/towns/townfirst306.html|title=Carron: Overview|work=Gazetteer for Scotland|accessdate=5 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC_Legacies_Carron\">{{citeweb|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/legacies/work/scotland/central_and_fife/article_1.shtml|title=Carron: Scotland's Forge|publisher=BBC|accessdate=20 Feb 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe factory of \"Roebuck, Garbett and Cadells\" was established on the north bank of Carron Water, two miles north of [[Falkirk]].  Taking [[iron ore]] from [[Bo'ness]] and water from the Carron, they decided to use the new method pioneered by [[Abraham Darby I|Abraham Darby]] at [[Coalbrookdale]], using [[Coke (fuel)|coke]] from [[coal mine]]s in the vicinity as fuel rather than the usual [[charcoal]].<ref name=\"HH28\">{{cite journal|last=Hamilton|first=Henry|year=1928|title=The Founding of Carron Ironworks|journal=Scottish Historical Review|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|volume=25|issue=99|jstor=25525835|pages=187\u2013190}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Devine|first=T.M.|title=The Scottish Nation 1700-2000|year=2000|publisher=Penguin|isbn=9780140230048|pages=106, 116}}</ref> The works helped to push other less technologically advanced ironworks, such as the [[Wealden iron industry]] based in [[the Weald]], out of business.\n\nCadell's young son, also William, was appointed manager, and the company's financial position was precarious in its first few years.  It took time and a considerable investment to create the necessary [[infrastructure]] and for the largely unskilled workforce to develop the techniques of iron working.  The first [[blast furnace]] became operational on 26 December 1760, producing [[pig iron]].  However, when the factory started to produce [[cast iron]] goods, they were of a generally poor quality.  Nevertheless, in 1764, the [[Board of Ordnance]] granted the company a lucrative contract to supply armaments to the [[United Kingdom|British]] armed forces.  The company also cast parts for [[James Watt]]'s [[steam engine]] in 1765.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Watters|first1=Brian|title=Carron, Where Iron Runs Like Water!|year=1998|publisher=John Donald|isbn=9780859765053|pages=35\u201339}}</ref>\n\nThe company's fortunes had begun to improve as a result of [[Charles Gascoigne]] becoming a partner in 1765.  Gascoigne was a grandson of Charles Elphinstone, 9th Lord Elphinstone and had married Samuel Garbett's daughter in 1759.  Gascoigne introduced many improvements in the company's techniques of production, and devoted considerable effort to increasing the quality of its work, and he took over the management of the works from William Cadell, Jr, in 1769.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Watters|first1=Brian|title=Carron, Where Iron Runs Like Water!|year=1998|publisher=John Donald|isbn=9780859765053|pages=49-108}}</ref>\n\nThe company's strict control over its supply of resources, including use of coal miners under conditions of life bondage, gave rise to disputes, with troops being called out to quell conflict on more than one occasion in the 1760s and 1770s.<ref>{{cite book|last=Duncan|first=Robert|title=The Mineworkers|year=2005|publisher=Birlinn|isbn=9781841583655|pages=49\u201352}}</ref>\n\nThe company received a [[royal charter]] to [[Incorporation (business)|incorporate]] as the Carron Company in 1773.<ref name=\"JN58\">{{cite journal|last=Norris|first=John|year=1958|title=The Struggle for Carron: Samuel Garbett and Charles Gascoigne|journal=Scottish Historical Review|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|volume=37|issue=124|jstor=25526479}}</ref>{{rp|139}} However, despite Gascoigne's efforts, the quality of company's products had remained low, and the company's contracts to supply the [[Royal Navy]] were cancelled in 1773, with the company's cannon being removed from all naval vessels. A representative of the [[Royal Artillery]], Captain Blair, inspected the Carron Works in 1774 and reported ongoing problems with quality and handling of the guns: \"on the death of [Carron Guns partner Ebenezer] Roebuck the Carron Guns had through the carelessness of the workmen very much deteriorated, and the firm lost ground.\"<ref name=RAI>{{cite journal|title=A List of the other Papers of the Society which are preserved|journal=The Journal of the Royal Artillery||volume=1|publisher=The Royal Artillery Institution|year=1858|page=21|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433009351143;view=1up;seq=39|accessdate=27 December 2018}}</ref> Despite this negative assessment, the report noted with approval that Charles Gascoigne was attempting to revive the firm.<ref name=RAI/>\n\n==Carronades==\n{{Main|Carronade}}\n[[File:Carronade at the Carron Works, near Falkirk.jpg|thumb|120px|right|A neglected [[carronade]] still on display at the former Carron Works]]\n[[File:Carronades made at the Carron Works, near Falkirk.jpg|thumb|120px|right|A pair of preserved [[carronade]]s in King Street, [[Stenhousemuir]]]]\n[[File:Carron Iron Oven-1844.JPG|thumb|120px|right|An iron [[oven]] manufactured by Carron Company Scotland]]\nGascoigne pushed forward the development of a new type of [[cannon]], originally known as the \"Gasconades\" but better known by its later name, the \"[[Carronade]]\".  It was shorter and much lighter than a [[long gun]] of the same calibre, meaning that more could be carried, and it was also quicker to load and required a smaller crew.  On the debit side, carronades had a short range.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Watters|first1=Brian|title=Carron, Where Iron Runs Like Water!|year=1998|publisher=John Donald|isbn=9780859765053|pages=74\u201385}}</ref>\n\nSome warships - mainly small ones - were equipped with carronades as their main or only armament, but such vessels were vulnerable to opponents armed with long guns.  The carronade's principal use was on the upper decks of warships, where batteries of carronades replaced smaller numbers of long guns.  This greatly increased firepower at the close ranges at which contemporary naval battles were usually fought, without impairing stability or sailing qualities.\n\nThe carronade was a considerable success, and remained in production from 1778 to the 1850s.  The company established such a reputation for quality that the [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington|Duke of Wellington]] remarked in a letter to Admiral Berkley in 1812<ref>{{cite book|last1=Watters|first1=Brian|title=Carron, Where Iron Runs Like Water! A New History of Carron Iron Works, 1759-1982|year=1998|publisher=John Donald|isbn=9780859765053|pages=298\u2013299}}</ref> that he only wanted cannon manufactured by the Carron Company in his army.  The company also made ammunition, including some invented by [[Henry Shrapnel]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Watters|first1=Brian|title=Carron, Where Iron Runs Like Water! A New History of Carron Iron Works, 1759-1982|year=1998|publisher=John Donald|isbn=9780859765053|pages=118-119}}</ref>\n\nThe company supplied armaments to governments outside the UK, including weapons supplied to the embryonic [[United States]] which were used against Britain in the [[War of 1812]].  The British government tried to prevent the company from supplying plans and equipment to the [[Russian Empire]], intended to improve [[Catherine the Great]]'s weapons foundry at [[Petrozavodsk]]; nonetheless, Gascoigne delivered the Russian's orders, and travelled to Russia in May 1786 to supervise the works.<ref name=\"JN58\"/>{{rp|141\u2013144}} He remained in Russia for 20 years, dying in July 1806 in [[Kolpino]] near [[St. Petersburg]] as [[Actual State Councillor]] Karl Karlovich Gaskoin.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Stewart|first1=A. F. |title=Scottish Influences in Russian History|year=1913|publisher=Glasgow, Maclehose}}</ref>\n\n==Prosperity and fall==\n[[File:BriefkastenCarronCompanyStirlingshire.JPG|thumb|200px|upright|The words \"Carron Company Stirlingshire\" appear near the base of many UK [[pillar box]]es]]\n\nBy 1814, the Carron Company was the largest iron works in Europe, employing over 2,000 workers, and it attracted many innovators.  [[William Symington]] <ref>{{cite book|last1=Watters|first1=Brian|title=Carron, Where Iron Runs Like Water!|publisher=John Donald|isbn=9780859765053|pages=116-118}}</ref>\nwas an engineer for the Carron Company in the early 19th century, and the company made engines for his [[steamboat]]s, the ''Experiment'' and the ''[[Charlotte Dundas]]''.  [[John Smeaton]] was a consultant for the company. [[Henry Cort]] <ref>{{cite book|last1=Watters|first1=Brian|title=Carron, Where Iron Runs Like Water!|year=1998|publisher=John Donald|isbn=9780859765053|pages=102-103}}</ref>\nexperimented on methods to produce malleable iron, anticipating the [[puddling (metallurgy)|puddling process]]. [[Benjamin Franklin]] visited the factory,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Watters|first1=Brian|title=Carron, Where Iron Runs Like Water!|year=1998|publisher=John Donald|isbn=9780859765053|pages=63\u201364}}</ref> leaving works and is said to have left a design for a stove called 'Dr Franklin's stove or the Philadelphia stove'.\n\nThe company produced [[pig iron]] throughout the 19th century, together with [[cast iron|cast-iron]] products such as balustrades, fire grates, and the Carron bathtub.  It ran its own [[shipping line]], and produced munitions in both [[World War]]s.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Watters|first1=Brian|title=Carron, Where Iron Runs Like Water!|year=1998|publisher=John Donald|isbn=9780859765053|pages=305-326}}</ref>It later became one of several foundries producing [[pillar box]]es and was one of five foundries casting Sir [[Giles Gilbert Scott]]'s classic [[Red telephone box]]es.  In the 1960s, it produced cast-iron rings to line the [[Tyne Tunnel]] under the [[River Tyne]] from [[Jarrow]] to [[Howdon]] and the [[Clyde Tunnel]] under the [[River Clyde]] from [[Whiteinch]] to [[Govan]] near Glasgow.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Watters|first1=Brian|title=Carron, Where Iron Runs Like Water!|year=1998|publisher=John Donald|isbn=9780859765053|pages=345\u2013346}}</ref>\n\n\nThe company diversified into [[plastic]]s and [[stainless steel]], but the works went into [[receivership]] in 1982.\n\n==Carron Phoenix==\nThe company was taken over and operates today under the name of Carron Phoenix, part of the [[Franke (company)|Franke]] corporation. Like its predecessor, The Carron Company, Carron Phoenix's headquarters are at the Carron Works in Falkirk.\n\nCarron Phoenix produces stainless steel, ceramic and granite moulded sinks which are sold around the world but some areas of production have been moved to China and Slovakia.\n\n[[File:Navagio carron detail.jpg|thumb|A detail from the famous [[MV Panagiotis|MV ''Panagiotis'']] shipwreck (aka [[Navagio]]), situated on a beach of the island of [[Zakynthos]], Greece.]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Abbotshaugh Community Woodland]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*''Where Iron Runs Like Water! A new history of Carron Iron Works 1759&ndash;1982'', Brian Watters, John Donald, 1998.\n*Campbell, R.H.  ''Carron Company'' (1961) Oliver and Boyd\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat}}\n*[http://www.carron.com/ Carron Official Website]\n*[http://www.falkirk-wheel.com/features/people-of-the-falkirk-area/59-charles-gascoigne Charles Gascoigne - The Darling of Carron Works]\n*[http://tompaterson.co.uk/mining/CarronCollieries.htm Carron Collieries]\n*[http://www.falkirklocalhistorysociety.co.uk/home/index.php?id=107 Falkirk Local History Society]\n*[http://www.crwflags.com/fotw/flags/gb~hfca.html#carron Flags of the shipping line]\n*[http://www.railscot.co.uk/Carron_Ironworks/frame.htm Chronology]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080705094516/http://www.falkirk.gov.uk/services/community/cultural_services/museums/museums_and_archives.aspx Falkirk Council currently hold the largest number of objects and amount of material associated with Carron]\n*[https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/2010846 Lines by Robert Burns on the Carron Ironworks]\n\n[[Category:Defence companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Ironworks and steelworks in Scotland]]\n[[Category:1759 establishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies disestablished in 1982]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies established in 1759]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Falkirk (council area)]]\n[[Category:1982 disestablishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Stenhousemuir]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=July 2009}}\n[[File:Carron Company trademark.jpg|thumb|right|The Carron Company [[trademark]] on the Carron Works]]\n[[File:Carron Company insignia.JPG|thumb|Carron Company insignia]]\nThe '''Carron Company''' was an [[ironworks]] established in 1759 on the banks of the [[River Carron (Forth)|River Carron]] near [[Falkirk]], in [[Stirlingshire]], Scotland.  After initial problems, the company was at the forefront of the [[Industrial Revolution]] in the [[United Kingdom]].  The company prospered through its development and production of a new short-range and short-barrelled naval [[cannon]], the [[carronade]].  The company was one of the largest iron works in Europe through the 19th century.  After 223 years, the company became [[insolvency|insolvent]] in 1982 and was later acquired by the [[Franke (company)|Franke Corporation]], being rebranded '''Carron Phoenix'''.\n\n==Early years==\n[[File:Clocktower entrance to the former Carron Works, near Falkirk.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Clocktower entrance to the Carron Works]]\n[[File:Dated iron lintel at the former Carron Works, near Falkirk.jpg|thumb|right|Fragment of the first [[blast furnace]] in the clocktower of the Carron Works]]\n[[File:James Watt steam engine relic at the Carron Works.JPG|thumb|right|[[Cylinder (engine)|Cylinder]] fragment of [[James Watt|Watt]]'s first operational [[steam engine]] at the Carron Works]]\n\nThe original founders of the Carron Works were: [[John Roebuck]], a [[medical doctor]] and [[chemist]] from [[Sheffield]]; his two brothers, Thomas Roebuck and Ebenezer Roebuck; [[Samuel Garbett]], a merchant from [[Birmingham]]; [[William Cadell]], Senior, an [[industrialist]] from a merchant family, from [[Cockenzie]], [[East Lothian]]; his son, William Cadell, Junior; and John Cadell.<ref name=\"GfS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.scottish-places.info/towns/townfirst306.html|title=Carron: Overview|work=Gazetteer for Scotland|accessdate=5 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC_Legacies_Carron\">{{citeweb|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/legacies/work/scotland/central_and_fife/article_1.shtml|title=Carron: Scotland's Forge|publisher=BBC|accessdate=20 Feb 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe factory of \"Roebuck, Garbett and Cadells\" was established on the north bank of Carron Water, two miles north of [[Falkirk]].  Taking [[iron ore]] from [[Bo'ness]] and water from the Carron, they decided to use the new method pioneered by [[Abraham Darby I|Abraham Darby]] at [[Coalbrookdale]], using [[Coke (fuel)|coke]] from [[coal mine]]s in the vicinity as fuel rather than the usual [[charcoal]].<ref name=\"HH28\">{{cite journal|last=Hamilton|first=Henry|year=1928|title=The Founding of Carron Ironworks|journal=Scottish Historical Review|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|volume=25|issue=99|jstor=25525835|pages=187\u2013190}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Devine|first=T.M.|title=The Scottish Nation 1700-2000|year=2000|publisher=Penguin|isbn=9780140230048|pages=106, 116}}</ref> The works helped to push other less technologically advanced ironworks, such as the [[Wealden iron industry]] based in [[the Weald]], out of business.\n\nCadell's young son, also William, was appointed manager, and the company's financial position was precarious in its first few years.  It took time and a considerable investment to create the necessary [[infrastructure]] and for the largely unskilled workforce to develop the techniques of iron working.  The first [[blast furnace]] became operational on 26 December 1760, producing [[pig iron]].  However, when the factory started to produce [[cast iron]] goods, they were of a generally poor quality.  Nevertheless, in 1764, the [[Board of Ordnance]] granted the company a lucrative contract to supply armaments to the [[United Kingdom|British]] armed forces.  The company also cast parts for [[James Watt]]'s [[steam engine]] in 1765.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Watters|first1=Brian|title=Carron, Where Iron Runs Like Water!|year=1998|publisher=John Donald|isbn=9780859765053|pages=35\u201339}}</ref>\n\nThe company's fortunes had begun to improve as a result of [[Charles Gascoigne]] becoming a partner in 1765.  Gascoigne was a grandson of Charles Elphinstone, 9th Lord Elphinstone and had married Samuel Garbett's daughter in 1759.  Gascoigne introduced many improvements in the company's techniques of production, and devoted considerable effort to increasing the quality of its work, and he took over the management of the works from William Cadell, Jr, in 1769.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Watters|first1=Brian|title=Carron, Where Iron Runs Like Water!|year=1998|publisher=John Donald|isbn=9780859765053|pages=49-108}}</ref>\n\nThe company's strict control over its supply of resources, including use of coal miners under conditions of life bondage, gave rise to disputes, with troops being called out to quell conflict on more than one occasion in the 1760s and 1770s.<ref>{{cite book|last=Duncan|first=Robert|title=The Mineworkers|year=2005|publisher=Birlinn|isbn=9781841583655|pages=49\u201352}}</ref>\n\nThe company received a [[royal charter]] to [[Incorporation (business)|incorporate]] as the Carron Company in 1773.<ref name=\"JN58\">{{cite journal|last=Norris|first=John|year=1958|title=The Struggle for Carron: Samuel Garbett and Charles Gascoigne|journal=Scottish Historical Review|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|volume=37|issue=124|jstor=25526479}}</ref>{{rp|139}} However, despite Gascoigne's efforts, the quality of company's products had remained low, and the company's contracts to supply the [[Royal Navy]] were cancelled in 1773, with the company's cannon being removed from all naval vessels. A representative of the