ps, where batteries of carronades replaced smaller numbers of long guns.  This greatly increased firepower at the close ranges at which contemporary naval battles were usually fought, without impairing stability or sailing qualities.\n\nThe carronade was a considerable success, and remained in production from 1778 to the 1850s.  The company established such a reputation for quality that the [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington|Duke of Wellington]] remarked in a letter to Admiral Berkley in 1812 that he only wanted cannon manufactured by the Carron Company in his army.  The company also made ammunition, including some invented by [[Henry Shrapnel]].\n\nThe company supplied armaments to governments outside the UK, including weapons supplied to the embryonic [[United States]] which were used against Britain in the [[War of 1812]].  The British government tried to prevent the company from supplying plans and equipment to the [[Russian Empire]], intended to improve [[Catherine the Great]]'s weapons foundry at [[Petrozavodsk]]; nonetheless, Gascoigne delivered the Russian's orders, and travelled to Russia in May 1786 to supervise the works.<ref name=\"JN58\"/>{{rp|141\u2013144}} He remained in Russia for 20 years, dying in July 1806 in [[Kolpino]] near [[St. Petersburg]] as [[Actual State Councillor]] Karl Karlovich Gaskoin.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Stewart|first1=A. F. |title=Scottish Influences in Russian History|year=1913|publisher=Glasgow, Maclehose}}</ref>\n\n==Prosperity and fall==\n[[File:BriefkastenCarronCompanyStirlingshire.JPG|thumb|200px|upright|The words \"Carron Company Stirlingshire\" appear near the base of many UK [[pillar box]]es]]\n\nBy 1814, the Carron Company was the largest iron works in Europe, employing over 2,000 workers, and it attracted many innovators.  [[William Symington]] <ref>{{cite book|last1=Watters|first1=Brian|title=Carron, Where Iron Runs Like Water!|publisher=John Donald|isbn=9780859765053|pages=116-118}}</ref>\nwas an engineer for the Carron Company in the early 19th century, and the company made engines for his [[steamboat]]s, the ''Experiment'' and the ''[[Charlotte Dundas]]''.  [[John Smeaton]] was a consultant for the company. [[Henry Cort]] <ref>{{cite book|last1=Watters|first1=Brian|title=Carron, Where Iron Runs Like Water!|year=1998|publisher=John Donald|isbn=9780859765053|pages=102-103}}</ref>\nexperimented on methods to produce malleable iron, anticipating the [[puddling (metallurgy)|puddling process]]. [[Benjamin Franklin]] visited the factory,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Watters|first1=Brian|title=Carron, Where Iron Runs Like Water!|year=1998|publisher=John Donald|isbn=9780859765053|pages=63\u201364}}</ref> leaving works and is said to have left a design for a stove called 'Dr Franklin's stove or the Philadelphia stove'.\n\nThe company produced [[pig iron]] throughout the 19th century, together with [[cast iron|cast-iron]] products such as balustrades, fire grates, and the Carron bathtub.  It ran its own [[shipping line]], and produced munitions in both [[World War]]s.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Watters|first1=Brian|title=Carron, Where Iron Runs Like Water!|year=1998|publisher=John Donald|isbn=9780859765053|pages=305-326}}</ref>It later became one of several foundries producing [[pillar box]]es and was one of five foundries casting Sir [[Giles Gilbert Scott]]'s classic [[Red telephone box]]es.  In the 1960s, it produced cast-iron rings to line the [[Tyne Tunnel]] under the [[River Tyne]] from [[Jarrow]] to [[Howdon]] and the [[Clyde Tunnel]] under the [[River Clyde]] from [[Whiteinch]] to [[Govan]] near Glasgow.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Watters|first1=Brian|title=Carron, Where Iron Runs Like Water!|year=1998|publisher=John Donald|isbn=9780859765053|pages=345\u2013346}}</ref>\n\n\nThe company diversified into [[plastic]]s and [[stainless steel]], but the works went into [[receivership]] in 1982.\n\n==Carron Phoenix==\nThe company was taken over and operates today under the name of Carron Phoenix, part of the [[Franke (company)|Franke]] corporation. Like its predecessor, The Carron Company, Carron Phoenix's headquarters are at the Carron Works in Falkirk.\n\nCarron Phoenix produces stainless steel, ceramic and granite moulded sinks which are sold around the world but some areas of production have been moved to China and Slovakia.\n\n[[File:Navagio carron detail.jpg|thumb|A detail from the famous [[MV Panagiotis|MV ''Panagiotis'']] shipwreck (aka [[Navagio]]), situated on a beach of the island of [[Zakynthos]], Greece.]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Abbotshaugh Community Woodland]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*''Where Iron Runs Like Water! A new history of Carron Iron Works 1759&ndash;1982'', Brian Watters, John Donald, 1998.\n*Campbell, R.H.  ''Carron Company'' (1961) Oliver and Boyd\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat}}\n*[http://www.carron.com/ Carron Official Website]\n*[http://www.falkirk-wheel.com/features/people-of-the-falkirk-area/59-charles-gascoigne Charles Gascoigne - The Darling of Carron Works]\n*[http://tompaterson.co.uk/mining/CarronCollieries.htm Carron Collieries]\n*[http://www.falkirklocalhistorysociety.co.uk/home/index.php?id=107 Falkirk Local History Society]\n*[http://www.crwflags.com/fotw/flags/gb~hfca.html#carron Flags of the shipping line]\n*[http://www.railscot.co.uk/Carron_Ironworks/frame.htm Chronology]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080705094516/http://www.falkirk.gov.uk/services/community/cultural_services/museums/museums_and_archives.aspx Falkirk Council currently hold the largest number of objects and amount of material associated with Carron]\n*[https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/2010846 Lines by Robert Burns on the Carron Ironworks]\n\n[[Category:Defence companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Ironworks and steelworks in Scotland]]\n[[Category:1759 establishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies disestablished in 1982]]\n[[Category:Manufactu